Always keep games organized.

This removes the useless option to not "Keep games organized" in Library preferences which, instead of copying files to a system subfolder, would copy to an "unsorted" folder. Now all files will be automatically copied to a system subfolder when the "Copy files to Game Library folder" option is used. This should also solve the problem of files for multi-disc games sometimes getting orphaned in the "unsorted" folder during a bad import, without the need for extra logic.

Update Mednafen submodule ref

Always move game files to trash when removing a game that was copied to the Game Library folder.

The expected behavior is that "deleted" games are actually deleted. But users tick the suppression checkboxes and forget there are two separate "delete" and "trash" dialogs which later leads to confusion. So when they "delete" a game from the Library, it still exists in the Game Library folder despite being removed from the datastore.

There is no good reason to keep "deleted" files in the Game Library folder when A) the user ~/Library folder has been hidden by default since 10.7 and B) users forget about them and end up with orphan files or, in the case of CD and M3U files, a frustrating import experience if CD files already exist in the Game Library folder.

Note: Users that have unchecked "Copy files to Game Library folder" will continue to have their files simply removed from the Library but not physically moved to trash.

Revert NSCell subclasses to Objective-C.

NSCell subclasses use NSCopyObject() to implement NSCopying, which doesn’t set retain counts properly (http://robnapier.net/implementing-nscopying), causing a crash when the Swift versions of the cells are copied, such as in a table view. Until table views are migrated to use view-based table views, use Objective-C implementations of NSCell subclasses.
Update Mednafen submodule ref

Don't start a download for cores that are already downloading.

Core updates get checked on app launch. Loading the core preferences panel starts another check for updates, and if core updates are still downloading, -startDownload: gets called again, triggering an assertion failure for a non-nil download session. So, return early if isDownloading is YES.
Update core submodule refs

Define Swift compilation flags in "Active Compilation Conditions".

"Active Compilation Conditions" is a new build setting in Xcode 8. It declares flags using -D, which we were explicitly doing in "Other Swift Flags".

Add OEBuildInfo helper class for exposing build-time macros to Swift.

OEBuildVersion.h is generated by a build-time script. Importing that header in Swift's bridging header causes Swift files and Objective-C files that import OpenEmu-Swift.h to be recompiled because the file has changed. OEBuildVersion exists to expose build-time generated macros to Swift without triggering recompilation.

Increase opacity of sidebar background color view.

Currently, switching from a non-Library collection to the Library
collection causes a noticeable "snap" in color as the background of the
NSVisualEffectView goes from non-vibrant to vibrant.

To lessen that effect until a long-term solution is implemented,
increasing the background color view's opacity lessens the vibrancy as
well as the "snap." Additionally, it better matches the translucency of
other system sidebars, and it reduces the smudgy effect vibrancy can
have when colorful content is behind it--letting our console artwork
be the center of attention.

Move system availability toggling from OEPrefLibraryController to OEDBSystem.

This fixes an issue where systems can't be hidden in the sidebar until the preferences window is loaded. OEDBSystem methods have been added that toggle a system's enabled property if certain conditions are true, either returning an error or presenting an error in an OEHUDAlert. Additionally, the notification OEDBSystemsDidChangeNotification has been renamed to OEDBSystemAvailabilityDidChangeNotification to be more specific. The notification is now posted whenever a system's enabled property is set, regardless of whether or not the property was modified through the aforementioned toggle methods. Move event handling from the UI process to the emulator process. Before this change, we needed 3 objects to be exchanged between the UI and emulator processes to have all the information. The last object was a proxy to the game core to receive the inputs from the UI process. This object is now removed and the device events are now handled on the emulator process side. This is achieved by moving the system responder to the emulator process which means it also needs to be set up on that side. To do so we add two OEGameCoreHelper methods that allows us to send the binding translations over to the emulator process.

This also means we move the so-called "global keys" (quick save, quick load, reset, pause, mute, etc.) management to the emulator process. Since the actual handle code is still on the UI process side we add these methods to the OEGameCoreOwner (formerly OEGameCoreDisplayHelper) protocol. OEGameDocument serves as the game core owner and handles all these new methods, it also sends the screen updates to its OEGameViewController and OEGameView. OpenEmuHelperApp now allocates both the core plug-in and system plug-in and their corresponding controllers to retrieve the events and pass them to the game core.

Finally, we also add a way to block events from being distributed to the game cores if the emulator window is not the frontmost one. Currently, this is handled using booleans but we could improve the whole architecture and allow different devices to be used on separate emulators running simultaneously by telling each emulator which devices they can use. Currently, this is only to prevent managing keyboard events if OpenEmu is not the frontmost app and preventing the emulators from handling any events while the preference window is shown.

Show HUD when launching games in fullscreen (to hide cursor)

This fixes a problem when launching games in fullscreen,
where the cursor would appear on the screen and not hide,
requiring further user interaction to make it disappear.

This happened because the full screen animation seems to
make the cursor appear on the screen, for reasons unknow to myself.

Simply hiding the cursor on NSWindowDidEnterFullScreenNotification,
instead of showing HUD controll bar, was also possibility,
but sometimes it wouldn't work, presumably because the event would
be triggered slightly before the fullscreen animation finished,
so the cursor would get displayed again.

Merge pull request #1318 from shnud/master

Attempt to improve scrolling speed

Attempt to improve scrolling speed

Scrolling was incredibly laggy on my Macbook, so I cached the images in
an NSCache - which will automatically get flushed when there’s low
memory.

The cache is populated on a background thread while the user scrolls,
and the grid view waits until scrolling has slowed or completely
stopped to update the images.

Note that it might need a bit of cleaning up. I’m a complete beginner
at Objective-C. Seems to work okay, though.

Merge pull request #1134 from joewreschnig/master

Avoid per-byte ObjC message when importing (~20% faster)

Rename md5ChunkSize to HASH_READ_CHUNK_SIZE and remove the unused crc32ChunkSize as the same read chunk is used for both hashes. Increase the chunk size from 10KB to 32KB. Optimize CRC32 inner loop to avoid calling the length message for each byte. Together these changes reduce total hash calculation time by about 20% when reading from an SSD.

Call glFlushRenderApple before running the core for a frame
This fixes #624.
Delaying the flush call until after running the core for a frame
caused glitches when the core changed screenSize while running.
Example: We set OpenGL to upload a videoBuffer and render it with
256x224, then run the core as it changes screenSize to 512x224.
Only then OpenGL uploads the videoBuffer as we call glFlushRenderApple
but it draws it with 256x224 texture coordinates.

Avoid handling duplicate devices

If one USB device is using 2 USB ports, we can get 2 callbacks for the
device from IOKit. Notably, a Das Keyboard ends up taking two device
handler spots, which means that any pressed key is processed twice.
Avoid this by testing if we're already handling the device in the IOKit
callback.

Ensure unarchived files have paths

When deceompressing an archived ROM, if the resulting path has no
extension, give it the extension of the archive. This allows us to
correctly import/play gzipped .smc files once again.

Fix retain cycle warnings on two recursive blocks

Recursive blocks retain themselves. This ends up being a retain cycle.
In one case, the retain cycle warning was valid. In another, the retain
cycle is explicitly broken, except clang doesn't know it.

In both cases, switch to capturing an __unsafe_unretained variable
instead.

Wii Classic Controller Pro support

Wii Remotes: Illuminate LEDs based on pair ordering.

Historically when pairing two Wii Remotes, they would both have the
first LED illuminated. This is unlike most other software that lights
up different LEDs.

With this change, we illuminate the LED corresponding to the pair
order of the Wii Remote. I.e., the first Wii Remote gets LED 1 lit,
the second gets LED 2 lit, etc. If there are more than 4 Wii Remotes,
we wrap around, so multiple Wii Remotes will have the same LEDs lit.

Support for new all new Wii Remotes with MotionPlus inside.

There are two types of Wii Remote at the time of writing: The
traditional ones and a newer variety that is more restrictive in how
one interacts with it. To support both, a few changes are required:

Discovery:

Newer Wii Remotes have a different minor device class than the older
ones, so a scan that simply looks for a particular major and minor
device class will miss at least one type of Wii Remote. To address
this, we scan for all bluetooth devices for 3 seconds, then check each
for a common prefix shared by the names of both types of Wii Remote
("Nintendo RVL-CNT-01" and "Nintendo RVL-CNT-01-TR").

Device Communication:

Historically, open-source Wii code has treated the Wii Remote like a
standard HID device and sent messages over the control channel with a
0x52 byte prefix, but unfortunately the newer Wii Remotes don't
receive messages sent like this. All Wii Remotes will accept messages
sent on the interrupt channel with a byte prefix of 0xa2, though, so
we change the code to use that.

To test this change, I paired 3 Wii Remotes simultaneously: One
Nintendo RVL-CNT-01 and two Nintendo RVL-CNT-01-TR. The -TR remotes
need to be disoverable by using the wrist strap to push the red button
on the back, while the non-TR one was made discoverable by holding
down buttons 1+2.

IOHIDEvent.m: triggerEventWithPadNumber: use proper maximum.

If this is set to value, as it is before this change, then value often
(always?) is initialized to 0, and then when the trigger is actually
used, there is an assertion failure b/c the value (positive number) is
beyond the maximum (0).

This was occurring when using a Wii Remote with Classic Controller
Pro.

Parse Wiimote Classic Controller Pro buttons correctly.

There were what appeared to by typos from copy-paste of Nunchuk code,
and also the Classic Controller uses a bit value of 0 to indicate a
button is pressed.

I only had a Classic Controller Pro (not a Classic Controller or
Nunchuk) to test with.

* libz:
  Transparently decompress gzipped ROMs at runtime

Transparently decompress gzipped ROMs at runtime

Teach OpenEmuHelperApp to detect when the ROM it wants to launch is
compressed in a fashion libz can handle (e.g. gzip). When this is
detected, decompress the file into TMPDIR and launch from there instead.

It should be pretty easy to add other decompression types, such as
bzip2, if needed.

Rewrite OEHUDWindow dragging

Give OEHUDWindow dragging a rewrite to match system behavior. Not only
does this cause it to behave correctly around the menubar, even on
multiple displays, it also fixes the issue where trackpad dragging could
get the window out of sync with the mouse.

Fixes #337.

Teach OEMenu to look at modifiers when it opens

OEMenu only looks at key modifiers when it receives the -flagsChanged:
event. This means that it will never show alternate menuitems unless a
modifier that it's interested in changes, even if one or more
interesting modifiers were already active when the menu first opened.

This exhibits today as saves cannot be deleted unless Option is pressed
while the menu is already visible.

Easier way to calculate the selection box.

Retrieve the min of the initial and current points, get the max of the two, and
build a rectangle that covers those two points. The min points are restricted by
the minimum boundary {0,1} and the max points are restricted by the maximum
boundary {CGGetMaxX(bounds), CGGetMaxY(bounds)}.  The origin of the selection box
is the min points while the size is max points subtracted by the min points.

When a rom is imported and only the visible cells need to be loaded, sometimes
there will be a ghost image of a cell's text. This change will attempt to
retrieve the visible cell that needs to be updated, attempts to dequeue a
reusable cell, and as a last resort creates a new cell.

This eliminates redundant calls while trying to reload a cell's properties.

Update UI when there are changes in database.

Monitor the main thread's MOC for added, removed, and changed 'Game'
entities. If games are added or removed, then reload the views. If the games'
properties are simply changed then just update the visible games.

-reloadData is an expensive operation as it has to calculate all of the
internal variables.  Each view (gridView, tableView, and coverFlowView) have
their own methods for reloading only the data of the visible cells. This is a
less intensive operation (compared to -reloadData) as the majority of the
cached values will remain.

Merge changes from thread's contexts when updated.

When a managed object context (MOC) is saved on a separate thread (other than
the main thread), those changes do not automatically propagate to the main
thread's MOC. By monitoring any changes made to other thread's MOCs we can
signal the main thread's MOC to update itself with those changes.

Fix memory semantics of error during import

NSError out-params are implicitly __autoreleasing, which means values
stuffed into them won't live past an @autoreleasepool boundary. Work
around this in one spot during import by using a local __strong variable
and stuffing it into the out-param once we exit the @autoreleasepool.

Turn off ARC for NSColor+OEAdditions.m

NSColor+OEAdditions.m defines an accessor on NSColor for -CGColor. This
method is designed to return an autoreleased CGColorRef calculated from
the NSColor. Under ARC, there is no supported mechanism to return an
autoreleased CF/CG object from a method, and the fact that this was
working was undocumented behavior of the compiler that may change in
future versions. As such, we need to turn off ARC for this file so we
can explicitly call -autorelease on the object.

Fix the declarations of -drawThemeFrame:

Turns out OECustomWindow does evil things with swizzles, so the
-draw%@ThemeRect: referenced in an earlier commit is, in fact,
-drawThemeFrame: in the subclasses. Fix up their implementations to deal
with the incoming NSRect instead of NSValue.

Switch from GDB to LLDB

Xcode 4.3 includes a much better version of LLDB, and it is now the
officially-recommended debugger. Plus, Xcode really wants to make this
change.

Fix an "Unsupported Configuration" warning with the nib

Xcode wants to update the nib to change its saved screen rect. Without
this, it's throwing an "Unsupported Configuration" warning because the
window ends up being outside the bounds of the (admittedly tiny) screen
rect. Updating for a larger screen rect removes this warning.

Squelch ImageKit warnings

ImageKit incorrectly declares its void *_reserved ivars as __strong,
which is illegal under ARC (as it is a non-object pointer). Importing
<Quartz/Quartz.h> instead of <ImageKit/ImageKit.h> squelches these
warnings, presumably because clang realizes Quartz is a system
framework.

Initialize AEGameAudio.contexts before creating the graph

Initialize AEGameAudio.contexts before creating the graph

If the contexts array is nil, the OEGameAudioContext objects get
dealloc'd in the middle of -createGraph. This causes the helper app to
crash in the audio callback. Unfortunately, the contexts array was nil,
because it wasn't being initialized until after -createGraph was called.
Initialize it a bit earlier.

Update GameCore / Background App with preliminary support for rendering directly to OpenGL

Game Core subclasses which wish to render directly to OpenGL can now
override the - (BOOL) rendersToOpenGL method to return yes. Render your
geometry during "executeFrame" - the renderDelegate will have an
appropriate GL Context setup and active for you. At this time, we do
not pass in a CGLContext, so if you need the context for any reason,
simply call CGLGetCurrentContext in your "executeFrame" method. No
appropriate context will be available outside of that method call.

Fix SNES hi-res mode by not resizing gameTexture -> IOSurface in the helper.

New stuff in OEGameCoreHelper:
-bufferSize returns the maximum size of the emu video.
The IOSurface is created at this size.
-screenSize returns the current size of the active texture in the IOSurface.

The window is opened at the screenSize of the first frame. screenSize
can change but it will be resized to the original screenSize (+ filter output)
ignoring the new aspect ratio.

The QC filters (CRT+TV) don't support non-square-pixel aspect ratio, so the game
texture is still upscaled to a square pixel ratio for them, which might lead to
a slight quality loss.

Video fixes, possibly.

- Fix randomly chosen malloc sizes used for video buffers
- Set client storage before calling glSubTexImage2D.
Eliminates a texture copy in cores using native pixel formats.
Texture range seems to be broken on my GPU but it no longer matters.
- Switch BSNES to a native pixel format.
- Set NTSC height for NTSC SNES games in both cores.
This fixes the game image being slightly stretched and blocky.
(I thought this was a vsync bug, but apparently not)
- Set SNES screen width/height to lowres.
This breaks hi-res (it got much uglier) but fixes all SNES low-res
frames being scaled 2x with nearest neighbor before reaching a filter.
Filters look like SNES9X Custom now.
- Restore the default scale factors for Scale2x/4x.

Fix for 10.6 changes in CA. Core Animation now uses a buffer of FBOs apparently, which messes up our caching of the parent FBO. We now cache it each frame. This is slowish, (glGets are to be avoided), but seemingly innocuous performance wise in 10.6. The QC Plugins will probably need to be updated as well, so things that render to an internal FBO dont also knock us out of the parent CALayer. There may be new 10.6 GL calls that let us avoid this glGet, will research.

fixed a small bug in GameDocument: when closing a game window, both windowWillClose and then windowWillResignKey get called.  windowWillClose release the gameCore but doesn't set it to nil, then windowWillResignKey attempts to pause gameCore, resulting in a bad access error.  Adding "gameCore = nil;" to windowWillClose fixed it.
